    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the rabbit analogy is okay but a bit weird lol. can u explain it without the magic stuff? like what is actually happening with the particle states? also what do people mean when they call it 'spooky action at a distance'?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! Quantum entanglement is a physical phenomenon that occurs when pairs or groups of particles interact in such a way that the quantum state of each particle cannot be described independently of the state of the others, even when the particles are separated by large distances. Imagine you have a pair of dice that are entangled. If you roll one die and it lands on six, the other die, no matter how far away it is, will also land on six when rolled. This is not because the dice are communicating with each other, but because their outcomes are intrinsically linked.\n\nThe term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was skeptical of this phenomenon. He referred to it as \"spooky\" because it seemed to imply that information could travel faster than the speed of light, which would contradict the theory of relativity. However, entanglement does not actually involve the transfer of information at superluminal speeds. When two particles are entangled, their properties are correlated in a way that is not possible in classical physics, but no usable information is transmitted between them in a way that would violate causality or the speed of light limit.\n\nIn essence, entangled particles are connected in such a way that the",
      "source": "target",
